        <h1><i class="fas fa-globe"></i> Cosmological Implications</h1>
        <p>
            The Unified Universe Theory provides new insights into the large-scale structure and behavior of the 
            universe. By introducing concepts like the <strong>Temporal Force</strong> and <strong>Temporal Displacement</strong>, 
            we can rethink the expansion of the universe, the distribution of dark matter, and the formation of 
            galaxies.
        </p>
        <p>
            The Temporal Force is thought to be a driving factor in the expansion of the universe, influencing the 
            rate at which galaxies move apart. The equation for the universe's scale factor in this theory is:
        </p>
        <div class="math-equation">
            <span>R(t) = R<sub>0</sub> * e<sup>F<sub>t</sub> * t</sup></span>
        </div>
        <p>
            Here, <strong>R(t)</strong> represents the scale factor of the universe, and <strong>R<sub>0</sub></strong> is the initial scale 
            factor. This exponential relationship suggests that the Temporal Force plays a key role in the accelerating 
            expansion of the universe, potentially offering an alternative explanation to dark energy.
        </p>

        <!-- Simplified Explanation -->
        <h2><i class="fas fa-lightbulb"></i> Simplified Explanation</h2>
        <p>
            Imagine the universe is like a loaf of bread with raisins scattered throughout. As the bread bakes, it expands, and the raisins move further apart. The raisins represent galaxies, and the expanding bread represents the expanding universe. The Temporal Force is like the heat that causes the bread to rise and expand. The bigger the loaf (or universe) gets, the more space there is between the raisins (or galaxies).
        </p>
        
